07114nam a22011055i 9783110646467DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021934662  a97831106464677 a10.1515/97831106464672doi  a(DE-B1597)512858  a(OCoLC)1253313763  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aQH343.4b.L52 2021 4aQH541.5.R63bL55 2021 7aSCI0080002bisacsh04a57722300aLife at Rock Surfaces :bChallenged by Extreme Light, Temperature and Hydration Fluctuations /ced. by Burkhard Büdel, Thomas Friedl. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (XIV, 244 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLife in Extreme Environments00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tVolume published in the series -- tContents -- tContributing authors -- t1 Functionality -- t1.1 The interface of rocks and microorganisms -- t1.2 The hypolithic habitat: microbial communities under translucent rocks -- t2 Organisms -- t2.1 Black fungi inhabiting rock surfaces -- t2.2 Cyanobacteria on rock surfaces -- t2.3 Lichens as pioneers on rock surfaces -- t2.4 High alpine lichens -- t2.5 Complex lichen communities inhabiting rock surfaces -- t2.6 Eukaryotic algal communities of rock surfaces -- t2.7 Desiccation-tolerant vascular plants: systematic distribution, ecology, and biogeography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRock surfaces provide a challenging habitat for a broad diversity of micro- or small-sized organisms. They interact with each other forming complex communities as well with their substrate causing biodeterioration of rock. Extreme fluctuation in light, temperature and hydration are the main factors that determine the rock surface habitats. The habitat includes epilithic organisms which thrive on the surface without penetrating the rock, endolithic organisms which live just beneath the surface using a thin layer of the rock surface for protection against adverse conditions of the environment (e.g. light protection, storage of water) and chasmo-endolithic organisms which use fractures of the rock surface for a more habitable environment. The book will provide an overview of the various organismal groups, from prokaryotes to vascular plants and arthropods, as well as survey organism-mediated interactions with the rock surface. The latter include biogenic weathering (biogeochemistry, state-of-the art imaging methods), photosynthesis and nitrogen fixation at and inside the rock surface.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEcology. 0aExtreme environmentsxMicrobiology. 0aGeobiology. 0aRocks. 4aBiogeochemistry. 4aLichens. 4aalgae. 4acyanobacteria. 4amicrobe. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Biology.2bisacsh1 aBüdel, Burkhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBüdel, Burkhard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aColeine, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCowan, Don A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarienko, Tatyana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedl, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedl, Thomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrube, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHauer, Tomáš, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJung, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaštovský, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomárek, Jiří, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1